<div class="bg-zinc-950 text-zinc-100">
  <.marketing_nav current_user={@current_user} current={:docs} />

  <section class="py-12 sm:py-16">
    <.docs_layout
      current="connect-an-llm"
      toc={[
        {"cloud-llm", "Connect a cloud LLM"},
        {"api-key", "Mint an API key"},
        {"stdio-bridge", "Desktop & CLI clients"},
        {"direct-http", "Direct MCP over HTTP"}
      ]}
    >
      <.docs_header current="connect-an-llm">
        <:dek>
          emisar exposes your runners and their action catalog as a Model
          Context Protocol server. Two ways to plug an LLM in:
        </:dek>
      </.docs_header>

      <ul class="mt-4 list-disc space-y-2 pl-6 text-sm text-zinc-300">
        <li>
          <strong>Remote MCP</strong> (Claude.ai, ChatGPT Apps, recent IDE
          clients) — enter a display name and the emisar server URL. emisar
          signs you in over OAuth; there is no API key or header to manage.
          Leave optional OAuth client credentials empty so the connector can
          register itself.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Stdio bridge or static key</strong> (Claude Desktop,
          Claude Code, Cursor, Windsurf, Zed, OpenClaw, OpenCode, Pi, Copilot CLI,
          Codex CLI, Gemini CLI, Goose, Hermes, Grok CLI, plain HTTP) — a tiny
          binary on your machine, or a raw bearer token, authenticated with
          an <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">emk-</code> API key.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <.agent_skill_cta
        class="mt-8"
        skill="connect-llm"
        prompt="Connect this machine's coding agent to my emisar account over MCP — install the emisar-mcp bridge, register the client, and prove a run end to end. First ask me which client I use. Use the connect-llm skill: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/AndrewDryga/emisar/main/skills/connect-llm/SKILL.md"
      >
        Or have your coding agent do it — the <code class="text-zinc-300">connect-llm</code>
        skill walks it through installing the bridge, registering your client, and proving a run
        end to end.
      </.agent_skill_cta>

      <figure class="mt-8 overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-zinc-800 shadow-lg shadow-black/30">
        <img
          src="/images/screenshots/connect-llm-agents.webp"
          alt="The Connect-an-agent client picker: cloud clients (Claude.ai, ChatGPT Apps) and local or IDE clients (Claude Code, Claude Desktop, Cursor, Windsurf, Zed, OpenClaw, OpenCode, Pi, Copilot CLI, Gemini CLI, Codex CLI, Goose, Hermes, Grok CLI). Cloud setup shows copyable connector-name and OAuth MCP server URL fields; local setup mints a bearer key and shows per-client setup steps."
          loading="lazy"
          class="w-full"
        />
      </figure>

      <%!-- ============================================================ --%>
      <%!-- Step 1: Remote MCP (OAuth)                                    --%>
      <%!-- ============================================================ --%>
      <section>
        <.docs_h2 id="cloud-llm">1 · Connect a cloud LLM</.docs_h2>

        <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
          Claude.ai and ChatGPT Apps ask for a display name and a <strong>server URL</strong>
          — no header or API key. emisar is a full OAuth&nbsp;2.1 authorization
          server, so the connector discovers it from that URL, registers itself
          automatically, and sends you through a one-time emisar sign-in. Enter
          these values:
        </p>

        <div class="mt-4 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
          <div class="grid border-b border-zinc-900 sm:grid-cols-[10rem_1fr] sm:items-center">
            <div class="px-3 pt-3 font-mono text-[11px] text-zinc-400 sm:py-3">
              connector name
            </div>
            <code class="break-all px-3 pb-3 text-xs text-zinc-300 sm:py-3">Emisar</code>
          </div>
          <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-[10rem_1fr] sm:items-center">
            <div class="px-3 pt-3 font-mono text-[11px] text-zinc-400 sm:py-3">
              remote MCP server URL
            </div>
            <code class="break-all px-3 pb-3 text-xs text-brand-300 sm:py-3">
              https://emisar.dev/api/mcp/rpc
            </code>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-10">
          <%!-- Claude.ai (cloud) --%>
          <section>
            <.docs_h3 id="claude-ai">Claude (claude.ai)</.docs_h3>
            <ol class="mt-3 list-decimal space-y-2 pl-6 text-sm text-zinc-300">
              <li>
                Open <strong>Settings → Connectors</strong>
                (on Pro/Max it's <strong>Customize → Connectors</strong>).
              </li>
              <li>
                Click <strong>+</strong> → <strong>Add custom connector</strong>.
              </li>
              <li>
                Enter <strong>Emisar</strong>
                as the <strong>Connector name</strong>, then paste the
                <strong>Remote MCP server URL</strong>
                above into the URL field.
              </li>
              <li>
                Leave <strong>Advanced settings</strong>
                (OAuth Client ID / Client Secret) <strong>empty</strong>
                —
                emisar registers your client for you via Dynamic Client
                Registration. Click <strong>Add</strong>.
              </li>
              <li>
                Claude opens an emisar tab. Sign in, review what the
                connector is asking for, and click <strong>Authorize</strong>. The connector flips on.
              </li>
              <li>
                Optional: open <strong>Settings → Connectors → Emisar</strong>. Under <strong>Tool permissions</strong>, set both
                <strong>Read-only tools</strong>
                and <strong>Write/delete tools</strong>
                to <strong>Always allow</strong>. This removes Claude's own per-tool prompts; emisar policy, approvals, and audit still apply.
              </li>
              <li>
                Turn it on for a chat: the <strong>+</strong> button (lower-left of the composer)
                → <strong>Connectors</strong> → toggle <strong>emisar</strong>.
              </li>
            </ol>
            <.docs_callout kind={:note}>
              <p>
                <strong class="text-zinc-400">Team / Enterprise:</strong>
                only an Owner can add the connector, under <strong>Settings → Organization settings → Connectors → Add → Custom → Web</strong>.
                Members then open <strong>Customize → Connectors</strong>
                and click <strong>Connect</strong>
                to run the same sign-in.
              </p>
            </.docs_callout>
          </section>

          <%!-- ChatGPT --%>
          <section>
            <.docs_h3 id="chatgpt">ChatGPT</.docs_h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
              ChatGPT reaches a custom MCP server through <strong>Developer mode</strong>. Available on all ChatGPT plans.
            </p>
            <ol class="mt-3 list-decimal space-y-2 pl-6 text-sm text-zinc-300">
              <li>
                Turn on Developer mode once — it's off by default and flagged <strong>Higher risk</strong>: <strong>Settings → Security and login</strong>, toggle <strong>Developer mode</strong>. (The same toggle sits at the bottom of <strong>Settings → Plugins</strong>.)
              </li>
              <li>
                Open <strong>Settings → Plugins</strong>
                (or <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">chatgpt.com/plugins</code>)
                and click <strong>Create</strong>.
              </li>
              <li>
                Fill the form:
                <ul class="mt-1 list-disc space-y-1 pl-6 text-zinc-400">
                  <li>
                    <strong>Name</strong>
                    — <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">emisar</code>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Description</strong> (optional) — e.g. "Run approved
                    infrastructure actions on my fleet."
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Connection</strong>
                    → <strong>Server URL</strong>, then paste
                    <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">
                      https://emisar.dev/api/mcp/rpc
                    </code>
                  </li>
                  <li><strong>Authentication</strong> — choose <strong>OAuth</strong></li>
                </ul>
                Check <strong>I understand and want to continue</strong>, then click <strong>Create</strong>.
              </li>
              <li>
                ChatGPT sends you to an emisar sign-in → <strong>Authorize</strong>. On success it
                lists the tools emisar advertises.
              </li>
              <li>
                Optional — stop the per-call prompts: open <strong>emisar</strong>
                under <strong>Settings → Plugins</strong>, go to <strong>Permissions</strong>, and
                switch it from <strong>Allow low-risk actions</strong>
                (the default) to <strong>Allow all actions</strong>. ChatGPT then stops asking before
                each call; emisar policy, approvals, and audit still apply, so the gate stays on the
                server, not ChatGPT's prompt.
              </li>
              <li>
                Use it from a <strong>new chat</strong>: click the <strong>+</strong>
                button near the composer, choose <strong>More</strong>, then select <strong>emisar</strong>. Seeing tools in settings only proves ChatGPT
                fetched metadata; this step adds emisar to the conversation context
                so the model can call it.
              </li>
              <li>
                After changing emisar's tool metadata, open the connector under
                <strong>Settings → Plugins</strong>
                and choose <strong>Refresh</strong>
                before testing
                again.
              </li>
            </ol>
            <p class="mt-3 text-xs leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
              ChatGPT connects to remote HTTPS MCP servers only — there is
              no stdio option. The emisar endpoint is already remote, so
              nothing extra to host.
            </p>
          </section>

          <%!-- What you're authorizing --%>
          <section>
            <.docs_h3 id="sign-in-grants">What the sign-in grants</.docs_h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
              The consent screen mints a key bound to <em>your</em>
              membership. The connector can only run actions your policy
              already permits, every call is attributed to you in the audit
              log, and anything needing approval still waits for a human.
              Revoke access any time from <strong>LLM agents</strong>
              in the dashboard, or from the connector settings in
              Claude / ChatGPT.
            </p>
          </section>
        </div>
      </section>

      <%!-- ============================================================ --%>
      <%!-- Step 2: API key (bridge + direct MCP)                        --%>
      <%!-- ============================================================ --%>
      <section>
        <.docs_h2 id="api-key">2 · Mint an API key (desktop, CLI &amp; direct MCP)</.docs_h2>

        <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
          The clients in steps 3 and 4 authenticate with a raw key instead
          of OAuth — but you rarely handle the key yourself. The installer in
          step 3 asks to add emisar to the clients it finds; you approve the
          connection in your browser and the keys are minted and written into
          the client configs for you. Setting up by hand instead? In the
          dashboard sidebar, click <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1.5 py-0.5 text-sm">LLM agents</code>,
          pick your client from the tab strip, and reveal the manual snippet —
          it mints a key named after the client, prefilled and ready to paste.
        </p>

        <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
          The key itself carries no permissions to tune — what it may run is your account
          <strong>policy</strong>
          (risky actions pause for approval), and which runners it can
          reach is the runner scope of the member who mints it (set on the <strong>Team</strong>
          page). To hand one agent a tighter blast radius, mint it under a member whose runner
          scope is already narrow. A separate read-only <strong>audit-export</strong>
          token —
          minted on the audit page — ships the audit log to a SIEM and can never execute an
          action. The dashboard reveals the raw key once; copy and store it.
        </p>

        <.docs_callout kind={:note}>
          <p>
            The cloud connectors in step 1 do <strong>not</strong>
            need an API key — they authenticate with OAuth. Mint a key only
            for the stdio bridge or plain-HTTP clients below.
          </p>
        </.docs_callout>
      </section>

      <%!-- ============================================================ --%>
      <%!-- Step 3: Stdio bridge                                          --%>
      <%!-- ============================================================ --%>
      <section>
        <.docs_h2 id="stdio-bridge">3 · Desktop &amp; CLI clients (stdio bridge)</.docs_h2>

        <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
          For clients that only speak stdio MCP — Claude Desktop, Claude
          Code, Cursor (local mode), Windsurf, Zed, OpenClaw, OpenCode, Pi,
          Copilot CLI, Gemini CLI, Codex CLI, Goose, Hermes, Grok CLI — install the
          tiny <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">emisar-mcp</code>
          binary. It's a thin shim that forwards stdio JSON-RPC frames
          to the same <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">/api/mcp/rpc</code>
          endpoint.
          Every MCP semantic — tool descriptors, content blocks,
          <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">wait_for_run</code>
          — is implemented in the portal,
          so the bridge stays version-locked to the spec without you
          redownloading it.
        </p>

        <.docs_h3 id="install-bridge">Install</.docs_h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-300">
          One-liner — auto-resolves the latest
          <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">mcp-v*</code>
          release, verifies sha256, drops
          <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">emisar-mcp</code>
          into <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">/usr/local/bin</code>:
        </p>
        <.docs_code
          phx-no-format
          label="shell"
          copy_text="curl -sSL https://emisar.dev/install-mcp.sh | sudo bash"
        ><span class="text-zinc-500">$</span> curl -sSL <span class="text-brand-300">https://emisar.dev/install-mcp.sh</span> | sudo bash</.docs_code>
        <p class="mt-2 text-xs leading-5 text-zinc-400">
          The installer is automated: it finds the LLM clients on the machine,
          and once you approve the connection in your browser it mints each
          client its own key and writes its config for you — your existing
          comments and other servers preserved. You shouldn't need the by-hand
          configs below; they're there for reference or an unattended setup.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-xs leading-5 text-zinc-400">
          Rather verify first? The bridge release carries SLSA provenance + a
          <code class="font-mono">SHA256SUMS-MCP</code>
          checksum file — see <.link
            href={~p"/trust" <> "#release-integrity"}
            class="text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
          >Release integrity</.link>.
        </p>

        <details class="group mt-8">
          <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between gap-4 rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/40 px-5 py-4 text-sm font-semibold text-zinc-100 transition-colors hover:bg-zinc-900/30">
            Set up a client by hand
            <.icon
              name="hero-chevron-down"
              class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-zinc-500 transition duration-200 group-hover:text-zinc-300 group-open:rotate-180 group-open:text-brand-400"
            />
          </summary>
          <div class="mt-6 space-y-8">
            <%!-- Claude Desktop --%>
            <section>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Claude Desktop</h3>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
                Add to <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json</code>:
              </p>
              <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
                <pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300">&#123;
  "mcpServers": &#123;
    "emisar": &#123;
      "command": "/usr/local/bin/emisar-mcp",
      "env": &#123;
        "EMISAR_URL": "https://emisar.dev",
        "EMISAR_API_KEY": "emk-...",
        "EMISAR_CLIENT": "claude-desktop"
      &#125;
    &#125;
  &#125;
&#125;</pre>
              </div>
              <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-400">
                Restart Claude Desktop. Tools appear under the tool icon
                as "emisar".
              </p>
            </section>

            <%!-- Cursor --%>
            <section>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Cursor</h3>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
                Same bridge. Cursor reads <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">~/.cursor/mcp.json</code>:
              </p>
              <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
                <pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300">&#123;
  "mcpServers": &#123;
    "emisar": &#123;
      "command": "/usr/local/bin/emisar-mcp",
      "env": &#123;
        "EMISAR_URL": "https://emisar.dev",
        "EMISAR_API_KEY": "emk-...",
        "EMISAR_CLIENT": "cursor"
      &#125;
    &#125;
  &#125;
&#125;</pre>
              </div>
              <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-400">
                Recent Cursor builds also speak remote MCP — point them at
                <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">/api/mcp/rpc</code>
                directly (step 1) if you'd rather skip the bridge.
              </p>
            </section>

            <%!-- Zed --%>
            <section>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Zed</h3>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
                The installer adds this for you and preserves your existing
                comments and servers. By hand, Zed reads
                <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">
                  ~/.config/zed/settings.json
                </code>
                and nests MCP servers under <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">context_servers</code>, not <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">mcpServers</code>:
              </p>
              <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
                <pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300">&#123;
  "context_servers": &#123;
    "emisar": &#123;
      "source": "custom",
      "command": "/usr/local/bin/emisar-mcp",
      "args": [],
      "env": &#123;
        "EMISAR_URL": "https://emisar.dev",
        "EMISAR_API_KEY": "emk-...",
        "EMISAR_CLIENT": "zed"
      &#125;
    &#125;
  &#125;
&#125;</pre>
              </div>
            </section>

            <%!-- Claude Code (CLI) --%>
            <section>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Claude Code</h3>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
                One-line register, user scope (every project):
              </p>
              <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
                <div class="border-b border-zinc-900 px-3 py-2 font-mono text-[11px] text-zinc-500">
                  terminal
                </div>
                <pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300"><span class="text-zinc-500">$</span> claude mcp add emisar --scope user \
    -e EMISAR_URL=https://emisar.dev \
    -e EMISAR_API_KEY=emk-... \
    -e EMISAR_CLIENT=claude-code \
    -- /usr/local/bin/emisar-mcp</pre>
              </div>
              <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-400">
                Verify with <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">claude mcp list</code>.
              </p>
            </section>

            <%!-- Gemini CLI --%>
            <section>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Gemini CLI</h3>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
                Add to <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">~/.gemini/settings.json</code>:
              </p>
              <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
                <pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300">&#123;
  "mcpServers": &#123;
    "emisar": &#123;
      "command": "/usr/local/bin/emisar-mcp",
      "env": &#123;
        "EMISAR_URL": "https://emisar.dev",
        "EMISAR_API_KEY": "emk-..."
      &#125;
    &#125;
  &#125;
&#125;</pre>
              </div>
            </section>

            <%!-- ChatGPT Codex CLI --%>
            <section>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">ChatGPT Codex CLI</h3>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
                Add to <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">~/.codex/config.toml</code>:
              </p>
              <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
                <pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300">[mcp_servers.emisar]
command = "/usr/local/bin/emisar-mcp"
env = &#123; EMISAR_URL = "https://emisar.dev", EMISAR_API_KEY = "emk-...", EMISAR_CLIENT = "codex" &#125;</pre>
              </div>
              <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-400">
                To let emisar calls run without Codex prompts, add
                <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">
                  default_tools_approval_mode = "approve"
                </code>
                below
                <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">[mcp_servers.emisar]</code>
                in <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">~/.codex/config.toml</code>.
                This trusts only the emisar MCP server; emisar still applies its own policies and approvals.
              </p>
            </section>

            <%!-- Grok CLI --%>
            <section>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Grok CLI</h3>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
                Register the bridge in your user config:
              </p>
              <div class="mt-3 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60">
                <div class="border-b border-zinc-900 px-3 py-2 font-mono text-[11px] text-zinc-500">
                  terminal
                </div>
                <pre class="overflow-x-auto p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300"><span class="text-zinc-500">$</span> grok mcp add emisar \
    -e EMISAR_URL=https://emisar.dev \
    -e EMISAR_API_KEY=emk-... \
    -e EMISAR_CLIENT=grok \
    -- /usr/local/bin/emisar-mcp</pre>
              </div>
              <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-400">
                To stop Grok's per-tool prompts for emisar only, add
                <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">"MCPTool(emisar__*)"</code>
                to <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">[permission].allow</code>
                in <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">~/.grok/config.toml</code>.
              </p>
            </section>
          </div>
        </details>

        <.docs_callout kind={:note}>
          <p>
            <strong class="text-zinc-400">Targeting a signed-dispatch runner?</strong>
            If a runner enforces <.link
              navigate={~p"/docs/signed-dispatch"}
              class="text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
            >signed dispatch</.link>, add
            <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">EMISAR_SIGNING_KEY</code>
            and <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">EMISAR_SIGNING_CERT</code>
            (printed by <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">emisar signing init</code>)
            to the same <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">env</code>
            block — the bridge signs every action dispatch so an enforcing runner will run it. Keep both secret,
            never on the portal. The cloud connectors in step&nbsp;1 sign nothing, so they can't reach an
            enforcing runner.
          </p>
        </.docs_callout>
      </section>

      <%!-- ============================================================ --%>
      <%!-- Step 4: Direct Streamable HTTP MCP                            --%>
      <%!-- ============================================================ --%>
      <section>
        <.docs_h2 id="direct-http">4 · Direct MCP over HTTP</.docs_h2>

        <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
          A custom MCP client can call the same Streamable HTTP endpoint with
          an <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">emk-</code>
          key from step 2. Tool discovery, calls, retries, and recovery all use
          the standard JSON-RPC MCP contract.
        </p>

        <.docs_code phx-no-format label="shell"><span class="text-zinc-500"># Try it from a shell — should return the tool list.</span>
<span class="text-zinc-500">$</span> curl -X POST <span class="text-brand-300">https://emisar.dev/api/mcp/rpc</span> \
    -H <span class="text-brand-300">"Authorization: Bearer $EMISAR_API_KEY"</span> \
    -H <span class="text-brand-300">"Content-Type: application/json"</span> \
    -d <span class="text-brand-300">'&#123;"jsonrpc":"2.0","id":1,"method":"tools/list"&#125;'</span></.docs_code>

        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-zinc-400">
          Send <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">initialize</code>,
          then use <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">tools/list</code>
          and <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">tools/call</code>.
          Every action dispatch must include a
          <code class="rounded bg-zinc-900 px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">reason</code>
          — it's logged to the audit trail and shown to approvers. Mutation
          retries are recovered through the operation ID returned by the MCP
          contract; clients do not invent a second retry key.
        </p>
      </section>
    </.docs_layout>
  </section>

  <.marketing_cta
    headline="Point your agent at real infrastructure — safely."
    subcopy="Set up a runner first, then connect Claude, ChatGPT, or Cursor to your account's MCP endpoint and let policy decide what runs."
    secondary_label="Read the quickstart"
    secondary_path={~p"/docs/quickstart"}
  />

  <.marketing_footer />
</div>
